goals.question: What is the distribution of airports by country?
goals.visualization: Bar chart of number of airports by country
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand which countries have the most and least number of airports. This information can be useful for airlines and airport management companies to identify potential markets and investment opportunities.

goals.question: What is the distribution of airports by type?
goals.visualization: Pie chart of number of airports by type
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the proportion of different types of airports such as small, medium, and large airports. This information can be useful for airlines and airport management companies to identify the types of airports they need to focus on for their operations.

goals.question: What is the busiest airport in terms of passenger traffic?
goals.visualization: Bar chart of top 10 airports by passenger traffic
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us identify the busiest airports in terms of passenger traffic. This information can be useful for airlines to identify the most popular airports and plan their routes accordingly.

goals.question: What is the distribution of airports by region?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the distribution of airports across different regions. This information can be useful for airlines and airport management companies to identify potential markets and investment opportunities.

goals.question: What is the trend of airport traffic over time?
goals.visualization: Line chart of airport traffic over time
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the trend of airport traffic over time. This information can be useful for airlines and airport management companies to identify seasonal patterns and plan their operations accordingly.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    # Group data by country and count the number of airports
    country_counts = data['country'].value_counts()

    # Create a bar chart of the number of airports by country
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 6))
    plt.bar(country_counts.index, country_counts.values)
    plt.xlabel('Country')
    plt.ylabel('Number of Airports')
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    plt.title('What is the distribution of airports by country?', wrap=True)

    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    airport_types = data['type'].value_counts()
    plt.pie(airport_types, labels=airport_types.index, autopct='%1.1f%%')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of airports by type?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend(airport_types.index, title="Airport Types", loc="best")
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    # Sort the data by passenger traffic and select the top 10 airports
    top_airports = data.sort_values(by='passenger_traffic', ascending=False).head(10)

    # Create a bar chart of the top 10 airports by passenger traffic
    ax = top_airports.plot.bar(x='airport_name', y='passenger_traffic', legend=False, color='b')
    
    # Set the title and labels
    plt.title('What is the busiest airport in terms of passenger traffic?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Airport Name')
    plt.ylabel('Passenger Traffic')
    
    # Rotate x-axis labels for better readability
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    
    # Add a horizontal line for the busiest airport
    busiest_airport_traffic = top_airports['passenger_traffic'].max()
    plt.axhline(busiest_airport_traffic, color='r', linestyle='--', label=f'Busiest Airport: {busiest_airport_traffic:.2f}')
    
    # Add the legend
    plt.legend()
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd
from mpl_toolkits.axes_grid1 import make_axes_locatable

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    # Read the world shapefile
    world = gpd.read_file(gpd.datasets.get_path('naturalearth_lowres'))

    # Convert the data to a GeoDataFrame
    gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame(data, geometry=gpd.points_from_xy(data.longitude, data.latitude))

    # Plot the world map
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 10))
    world.boundary.plot(ax=ax, linewidth=1)

    # Plot the airports by region
    gdf.plot(ax=ax, column='region', legend=True, markersize=5, cmap='viridis', legend_kwds={'loc': 'lower left'})

    # Set the title
    plt.title('What is the distribution of airports by region?', wrap=True)

    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]
    
    data = data.groupby('date')['traffic'].sum().reset_index()
    
    plt.plot(data['date'], data['traffic'])
    plt.xlabel('Date')
    plt.ylabel('Airport Traffic')
    plt.title('What is the trend of airport traffic over time?', wrap=True)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
